      <hedline>
        <hl1>Giuliani Policy's Price</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter from Susie Zeiger says she does not share regret of May 11 letter writer that Mayor Rudolph W Giuliani may withdraw from Senate race; says his 'quality of life' improvements in city have resulted in fear, intimidation and harassment for New Yorkers of color</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>A May 11 letter writer is ''profoundly saddened'' that ''Republicans are scurrying for a new Senate candidate'' to replace Rudolph W. Giuliani. If she understood the price that innocent people of color have paid for the return of ''respect'' to New York City, her praise might turn to criticism. ''Quality of life'' improvements have resulted in fear, intimidation and harassment for New Yorkers of color.</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>A May 11 letter writer is ''profoundly saddened'' that ''Republicans are scurrying for a new Senate candidate'' to replace Rudolph W. Giuliani. If she understood the price that innocent people of color have paid for the return of ''respect'' to New York City, her praise might turn to criticism. ''Quality of life'' improvements have resulted in fear, intimidation and harassment for New Yorkers of color.</p>
        <p>As a middle-aged Jewish woman, born and bred in the city, who works with immigrants, I am appalled.</p>
        <p>SUSIE ZEIGER  Brooklyn, May 12, 2000</p>
      </block>
